               <msContents>
                  <summary>A copy of the Persian <title xml:lang="fa-Latn-x-lc" key="work_499"
                        >Bayān</title>, which Browne describes as "a work of such capital
                     importance" that he has quoted it repeatedly elsewhere. He directs readers to
                     Baron Rosen's full statement of its contents (Collections Scientifiques, iii,
                     pp. 1-82) rather than repeating them here.</summary>
                  <msItem xml:id="F_12-item1">
                     <author key="person_9878408" ref="http://viaf.org/viaf/9878408/">
                        <persName xml:lang="ar-Latn-x-lc" type="standard">Bāb, ʻAlī Muḥammad
                           Shīrāzī, 1819-1850</persName>
                        <persName xml:lang="en">The Bāb</persName>
                        <persName xml:lang="ar">باب، ميرزا علي محمد</persName>
                     </author>
                     <title xml:lang="fa-Latn-x-lc" key="work_499">Bayān-i farsī</title>
                     <title xml:lang="fa" key="work_499">بيان فرسى</title>
                     <incipit xml:lang="ar"/>
                     <explicit xml:lang="ar" defective="true"/>
                     <colophon>Ends with what Browne calls an "abominably ungrammatical"
                        colophon.</colophon>
                     <note>
                        <foreign xml:lang="ar"/>
                     </note>
                     <listBibl>
                        <bibl>
                           <ref target="https://cudl.lib.cam.ac.uk/view/PR-A-00233-00004/85"
                              >p.59</ref>
                        </bibl>
                        <bibl>See sub classmark <idno>BBC. 3</idno> in Browne's "Catalogue and
                           Description of 27 Bābī Manuscripts", in Journal of the Royal Asiatic
                           Society of Great Britain and Ireland (Jul., 1892): 433-499.</bibl>
                        <bibl type="text-relations"/>
                     </listBibl>
                     <textLang mainLang="fa">Persian</textLang>
                  </msItem>
               </msContents>
               <physDesc>
                  <objectDesc form="codex">
                     <supportDesc material="paper">
                        <support>Paper</support>
                        <extent>114 folios (f. 1a, f. 114a, and f. 114b blank), in oblong
                           ("pocket-book") format <dimensions type="leaf" unit="cm">
                              <height>21.5</height>ß
                              <width>11</width>
                           </dimensions>
                        </extent>
                     </supportDesc>
                     <layoutDesc>
                        <layout writtenLines="21 30">Lines run parallel to the spine and shorter
                           side of the book, unevenly distributed, from 21 to 30 per page.</layout>
                     </layoutDesc>
                  </objectDesc>
                  <handDesc>
                     <handNote scope="major" script="shikastah" medium="blue">Written in bluish ink,
                        in an unformed and ungraceful nim-shikastah hand. Chapter headings written
                        in red.</handNote>
                  </handDesc>
               </physDesc>
               <history>
                  <origin>On the final blank leaf (<locus from="114v" to="114v">f. 114b</locus>) are
                     several dated notes, apparently recording the births of a former owner's
                     children; the earliest is dated Muḥarram 22nd, [12]82 AH (17 June <origDate
                        calendar="Gregorian" notAfter="1865">1865</origDate>), from which Browne
                     infers the manuscript was transcribed before that date. <quote xml:lang="ar"
                        cert="low" resp="#ocr-draft">قد تمّت الکلام من لسان العبد ملک العلام على يد
                        هذا الغلام...</quote></origin>
                  <provenance when="1888">Given to E. G. Browne, "after much urgent entreaty," at
                        <placeName key="place_8900669">Rafsinján</placeName>, near
                     <placeName key="place_7002134">Kirmán</placeName>, on 22 August <date when="1888">1888</date> -
                     per Browne's general introduction, his last manuscript acquired in Persia.</provenance>
                  <acquisition when="1936">Passed to <placeName>Cambridge</placeName> University
                     Library in <date when="1936">1936 </date>(the "Browne
                     Bequest").</acquisition>
               </history>

